1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,432
The syntax of classical propositional logic is given by a calculus. There

2
00:00:04,532 --> 00:00:08,282
are many calculi which turn out to be equivalent, but each has

3
00:00:08,382 --> 00:00:12,255
a set of axioms, which are just some logically valid formulas...

4
00:00:12,333 --> 00:00:16,021
...and rules of inference, which allow us to derive new

5
00:00:16,121 --> 00:00:19,808
formulas from a set of premises while preserving truth.

6
00:00:19,866 --> 00:00:24,307
The most concise calculus is the Hilbert style calculus, which has

7
00:00:24,407 --> 00:00:28,229
the following 3 axioms, and the only rule of inference is

8
00:00:28,329 --> 00:00:31,876
Modus Ponens, which says that if you have phi and you

9
00:00:31,976 --> 00:00:35,178
have phi implies psi, then you can conclude psi.

10
00:00:35,266 --> 00:00:39,263
These axioms seem random at first, and you may notice that

11
00:00:39,363 --> 00:00:43,855
conjunction and disjunction do not appear, but one can prove that

12
00:00:43,955 --> 00:00:48,306
they are both necessary and sufficient for propositional logic.

13
00:00:49,400 --> 00:00:53,021
Once we have our calculus, we can start to construct proofs.

14
00:00:53,121 --> 00:00:56,866
We can visualize proofs as trees, where the leaves are axioms,

15
00:00:56,966 --> 00:00:59,905
and we combine nodes using our rule of inference.

16
00:01:01,133 --> 00:01:05,743
Proofs can also be seen as computer programs. Where the axioms can be

17
00:01:05,843 --> 00:01:10,385
used as inputs, and modus ponens is seen as running a given program.

18
00:01:10,466 --> 00:01:14,824
Since phi implies psi can be interpreted as a computer

19
00:01:14,924 --> 00:01:19,117
program which if given phi as input, can output psi.

20
00:01:19,266 --> 00:01:23,456
So, an application of Modus Ponens is akin to running a computer

21
00:01:23,556 --> 00:01:28,417
program. The complexity, and therefore power, comes from the fact that the

22
00:01:28,517 --> 00:01:31,836
input formula phi, can be seen as a program itself.

23
00:01:31,933 --> 00:01:34,890
So we can pass programs as input to other programs. I

24
00:01:34,990 --> 00:01:37,890
will cover this in more detail in a later video, but

25
00:01:37,990 --> 00:01:40,947
for now just know that the world of syntax deals with

26
00:01:41,047 --> 00:01:44,293
formal proofs, and proofs can be carried out by computers.

27
00:01:45,333 --> 00:01:49,256
There are two main questions we can ask about our calculus.

28
00:01:49,333 --> 00:01:53,350
The first is whether we can trust it. Meaning if we prove something

29
00:01:53,450 --> 00:01:56,730
in our calculus, how do we know that it is really true?

30
00:01:56,800 --> 00:01:59,955
In propositional logic this is easy to check,

31
00:02:00,055 --> 00:02:03,282
since each of the axioms is logically valid...

32
00:02:03,333 --> 00:02:07,935
...again this means that each row in their truth table evaluates to 1.

33
00:02:08,133 --> 00:02:12,681
And clearly Modus Ponens preserves truth. So whatever we prove will

34
00:02:12,781 --> 00:02:16,705
be logically valid. This means that our calculus is sound.

35
00:02:17,800 --> 00:02:20,610
The second question is whether this list

36
00:02:20,710 --> 00:02:23,812
is sufficient to prove all valid statements?

37
00:02:23,866 --> 00:02:27,428
So, if we come across some arbitrary formula phi, and we

38
00:02:27,528 --> 00:02:31,090
check the truth table, and see that all rows evaluate to

39
00:02:31,190 --> 00:02:34,294
1, can we guarantee that there is a proof of phi?

40
00:02:34,400 --> 00:02:38,097
Perhaps there is some valid statement out there which no matter

41
00:02:38,197 --> 00:02:41,232
how hard we try, we cannot prove. Perhaps we need to

42
00:02:41,332 --> 00:02:44,487
add more axioms? This is the question of completeness.

43
00:02:44,533 --> 00:02:47,785
It turns out that this set of axioms is complete and we

44
00:02:47,885 --> 00:02:51,199
will see a stronger version of this in the fourth video.

45
00:02:51,266 --> 00:02:55,751
So, this simple calculus can only prove logically valid

46
00:02:55,851 --> 00:03:00,753
statements, and it can prove all logically valid statements.

